<dl id="n54121e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54121e">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54121e"> 121(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> only the / son of another, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54121e"><li>FW 109.06 </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n54121e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n54121e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54121e">MS BL 47476a-208</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:439 <a name="ed11" href="../../ff/fdra/eda.htm#ed11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed11.htm#n54121e">Draft: I.5&sect;1.11</a>/4.11</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Lao-tsze to Master Kung]</font> &lsquo;Shrewd and clever people are always near to death, for they love to criticise and pass judgment on others. Those who know a great deal about practical affairs, and do things on a large scale, endanger their persons, for by their actions and their knowledge they reveal the mistakes of mankind. He who is <mark>only the son of another</mark> has nothing for himself, for he owes all to his father; he who is only the official of another has nothing for himself, for he owes all to his superior.&lsquo; <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 103f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
